import networkx as nx
from IPython.display import display, SVG
import io
# Use graphviz Python package to render
import graphviz


# Create a small graph
G = nx.Graph()
G.add_edges_from([
    ('A', 'B'),
    ('B', 'C'),
    ('C', 'D'),
    ('D', 'A'),
    ('A', 'C')
])

# Generate DOT format string
dot_string = nx.nx_pydot.to_pydot(G).to_string()
# print("DOT format:")
# print(dot_string)


dot = graphviz.Source(dot_string)
dot.format = 'svg'
display(SVG(dot.pipe()))

Developer Guide
If you are new to using nbdev here are some useful pointers to get you started.

Install mytestrepo in Development mode
# make sure mytestrepo package is installed in development mode
$ pip install -e .

# make changes under nbs/ directory
# ...

# compile to have changes apply to mytestrepo
$ nbdev_prepare

title: mytestrepo
text:
Usage

Installation
Install latest from the GitHub repository:
$ pip install git+https://github.com/akrishnamo/mytestrepo.git
or from conda
$ conda install -c akrishnamo mytestrepo
or from pypi
$ pip install mytestrepo


Documentation
Documentation can be found hosted on this GitHub repository’s pages. Additionally you can find package manager specific guidelines on conda and pypi respectively.
